So many people do check box travel. They just want to see the Eiffel Tower, Montmartre, the Colosseum, and tick their boxes off of things to do, take a few selfies , and move on. I have done both styles of traveling - slow versus marching to the beat. I've woken up at 5am in the morning to drag my weary body out of the bed, still suffering form jet lag, so that I can rush into a jam packed tour bus to see all the tourist attractions. I've traveled completely aimlessly, ending up in a random antique store in Amsterdam, examining a microscope from the 1500's. I must say, those who are traveling to check off all the boxes and maximizing efficiency are completely missing the point of traveling. Such people should really stick with Google images and Wikipedia to get their efficiency in.

I, for one, welcome the spread of slow travel.

Life is a journey and I am sure you will have a wonderful life ahead of you keep doing keep dreaming and continue chasing them and build them.

Thanks for your continuing efforts to improve your use of the platform you have built for yourself. Your thoughtfulness and compassion are the most compelling elements of what you do. Pursuing the implications of that fundament, when the impulse of so many people is and would be not to break a successful formula, puts you and your channel into a tiny category of exceptional creators of vlog stories.

Whole discipline and habit support any extended project and our lives in multiple ways, it's important to leave room to grow in the ways, for example, you discuss in this video.

Not less importantly, you must listen to your body telling you in many ways, depending on the circumstances, when rest and healing become necessary. Those ways may include signs much less obvious than hypersensitivity to a nasty set of bedbug bites and the inflammation that follows. The signs must be heeded, sometimes even when they're subtle. Mind your body and mind. We all have limits, and those limits can surprise us - especially when we do not listen well to our bodies.

That said, please do bring the mindfulness - to your video windows on the world and to your personal life.

Thank you for the care you show to the people your meet and the places you visit.

Thank you as well for sharing your work. You make it possible for those of us dealing with issues - in my case, long-term illness (I hope longer-term illness, since there appears to be no good way out) - that keep us from continuing or even beginning our own journeys to experience our still-beautiful world.

Congratulations, finally, on freeing your diet from the gustatory ball and chain of animal butchery. You give your meals freedom and space to explore the world of food beyond dead relatives and so-called side dishes. The not-murdered animals thank you, the world thanks you, and I welcome you.

Be well.
